This is the story of how I once nearly got kidnapped and ended up in the trunk of a red Mazda.
A day after completing my design studies, I had a yard sale.
A guy in the red Mazda stopped and checked out my stuff.
He bought one of my artworks.
He was alone in the city and was just taking a road trip across the country. Afterwards, he would join the Peace Corps.
I invited him for a beer. He enthusiastically told me about how he wanted to change the world.
It was getting late. I was getting tired.
While we were settling the bill, I made the mistake of asking him, "Where are you sleeping tonight?"
He made the whole situation even worse: "I don't know yet."
And I thought: "Oh, man!
What do I do now?
Who doesn't know the situation?
Do I have to offer a place to sleep now?
But I've just met him! He says he's going to join the Peace Corps, but I don't know if he really plans to. I don't want to end up kidnapped in the trunk of a Mazda!
This is a small trunk!
Then I heard myself say, "I have an air mattress. You can sleep in my living room."
A voice in my head said, "Uh, what?"
At night, I lay in bed, staring at the ceiling, thinking: "Oh man! What have I gotten myself into?
A complete stranger is sleeping in my living room.
What if he's crazy?
I got so scared that I got out of bed, tiptoed to the door, and locked my bedroom door.
But he wasn't crazy at all.
We are still in touch.
The artwork he bought from me now hangs in his classroom. He is now a teacher.
That was my first experience as a host. It completely changed my perspective.
Maybe the people who were sold to me as strangers in childhood were actually friends just waiting to be discovered?
Hosting people on my air mattress became the norm for me. When I moved to San Francisco, I took the air mattress along.
