Last week we discovered something new.
We conducted a study with Stanford. We investigated how likely it is for people to trust each other, depending on how similar they are in terms of age and location.
Unsurprisingly, we trust people the most who are most similar to us.
The more differences we find, the less we trust.
This is a natural social bias.
Things get interesting when you add a person's reputation to the mix -- in our case, through reviews.
If you have fewer than three reviews, nothing changes.
But with more than ten, everything changes.
A good reputation highlights commonalities.
The right design can therefore help us overcome some of our deeply ingrained preferences.
We also learned that trust depends on how much one reveals about themselves.
Here you see the reactions to the first message from a guest.
If you share too little, like simply saying "Hi!", you're less likely to get a response.
If you share too much, like saying: "I have problems with my mother" -- the request is also less likely to be accepted.
There is therefore an optimal level of openness, for example, "Great artworks in your place! I'm vacationing with my family."
How can we use design to achieve this level of openness?
We use the size of the text field to recommend the right amount of text. We also provide tips on what topics one should write about.
Our entire company is built on the hope that the right design can help us overcome our prejudices against strangers.
